00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:38.633
Chemical properties: so let's put
something up as a hypothesis.

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:11.000
Let's say, well, maybe it has to do
with the energy that it takes to

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.500
remove electrons.
And, one other thing that I failed

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:22.000
to point out, if you take a look at
the energies associated with the

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.500
outermost electrons,
in this case, lithium,

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:33.000
you see it's 0.5 megajoules per mole,
and then what's the 6.26?

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:56.710
That's associated with one,
n equals one, inner shell. There is

00:00:56.710 --> 00:01:00.420
a huge difference between the
energies in the outermost shell and

00:01:00.420 --> 00:01:04.140
the inner shells,
which tells you that it's unlikely

00:01:04.140 --> 00:01:07.850
that any electrons except those in
the outermost shell are going to be

00:01:07.850 --> 00:01:11.570
active. The inner electrons are so
tightly bound that they are for all

00:01:11.570 --> 00:01:15.280
intents and purposes,
immobilized when it comes to

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:34.360
reactivity. Again, boron
is a good example.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:22.690
Look, 0.8, 1.36.
This is 2p. This is 2s.

00:01:22.690 --> 00:01:26.380
Yeah, they're different but they
are roughly on the order of about 1

00:01:26.380 --> 00:01:30.070
MJ per mole. If you go down to 1s,
it's 20 MJ per mole. So, the

00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:33.760
chances of getting any activity from
these inner shell of electrons are

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:37.460
vanishingly small.
So, let's focus on the outer shell

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:41.150
electrons. And,
these outer shell electrons are

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:46.810
termed valence electrons.
So let's construct a model here that

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:54.450
suggests that chemical reactivity is
somehow related to the electron

00:01:54.450 --> 00:02:02.090
binding energies of the outermost
electrons of the outermost shell.

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:09.720
And, this outermost shell is termed
the valence shell.

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:17.360
So, in a first blush,
you might say, well, why don't we

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:32.186
just take the first
ionization energy?

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:28.460
And, that's not a bad first guess.
But, we know for example that

00:02:28.460 --> 00:02:31.930
magnesium, when it reacts,
it reacts with both of its electrons,

00:02:31.930 --> 00:02:35.390
not just one of its electrons.
So, taking just the outermost

00:02:35.390 --> 00:02:38.860
electron might give us some false
readings. So,

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:42.330
what if we capture all of the
valence electrons.

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:45.790
Is there some way of handling that?
Because that will take care of all

00:02:45.790 --> 00:02:49.260
of the electrons that are capable of
reacting, none of the inner

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:53.900
shell electrons.
And we do so by a quantity called

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:59.720
the average valence electron energy.
In other words, if the average

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:05.540
energy of all the valence electrons.
So, let's take a look at an example.

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:11.360
An example of that might be,
oh, let's look at something like

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:17.180
oxygen. If you look at oxygen,
oxygen is 1s2, which is an inner

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:34.760
shell electron.
Just putting it up for completeness.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:29.460
2s2, and 2p4, and so here's the
valence shell.

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:35.920
If I want to take the average
energy of all of those,

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:42.380
what I can do is go over to my data
set. Here's a data set.

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:48.840
There is oxygen. The 2p is 1.
1. The 2s is 3.12. So then, I

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:55.300
could say that the average valence
electron energy for oxygen would

00:03:55.300 --> 00:04:01.760
then be, I've got two s electrons.
So, it's two times 3.12 plus four

00:04:01.760 --> 00:04:19.786
times 1.31, all divided by six.
I'm averaging it over the entire set

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:54.600
of valence electrons which gives me
1.91 MJ per mole.

00:03:54.600 --> 00:04:01.000
Or, in my favorite unit,
19.80 electron volts.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:25.920
This is electron volts per atom.
So, how does average valence

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:30.840
electron energy very across the
periodic table?

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:35.760
Let's take a look at that.
So, we see it here. We see that it

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:40.690
varies monotonically from left to
right as we move along a row.

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:45.610
So, this is a constant n number.
Within a constant shell, it varies

00:04:45.610 --> 00:04:50.530
from left to right,
maximally taking value at the right

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:55.750
extreme.
And, within a column,

00:04:55.750 --> 00:05:01.250
it decreases down a column.
It rises up a row. It decreases

00:05:01.250 --> 00:05:06.750
down the column.
And, the values that it takes can

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:12.250
be broken into three groups.
Over here in the lower left corner,

00:05:12.250 --> 00:05:17.750
we have elements that as a group
have very low values of average

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:23.250
valence electron energy.
These are elements that are good

00:05:23.250 --> 00:05:28.770
electron donors.
They are good electron donors

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:34.330
because the electrons aren't tightly
bound. OK, elements with low

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:39.880
average valence electron energy,
and here I'm saying below 11

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:45.440
electron volts,
these are good electron donors.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:06:02.813
And, we call these in simple
English, metals.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:56.070
And, it turns out that about 75% of
the periodic table falls into this

00:05:56.070 --> 00:06:01.150
category. So,
the vast majority of elements in the

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:06.220
periodic table are metals.
And, at the other extreme,

00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:11.300
we have elements with very high
value, elements with high average

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:16.380
valence electron energy.
Well, we just did the calculation

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:21.460
for oxygen. This is almost 20 eV,
high average valence electron energy,

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:26.890
greater than 13 electron volts.
So, that means the electrons are

00:06:26.890 --> 00:06:32.690
tightly bound.
So, these are poor electron donors.

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:38.490
And, in fact, if any electron comes
in their midst,

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:44.290
they'll capture it because the
binding energy is so high.

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:50.090
So, these are poor electron donors
but also a good electron acceptors,

00:06:50.090 --> 00:06:55.570
and we call these non-metals.
And you see those.

00:06:55.570 --> 00:07:00.710
And then there is this group of
about half a dozen right down the

00:07:00.710 --> 00:07:05.850
diagonal middle.
And, they have intermediate values.

00:07:05.850 --> 00:07:10.990
So, when the value of the average
valence electron energy lies between

00:07:10.990 --> 00:07:16.140
11 eV and 13 eV,
we have these elements that are

00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:21.280
neither fish nor fowl,
and you'll see in a little bit their

00:07:21.280 --> 00:07:26.420
unique electrical properties.
And, these are called semi-metals

00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:30.830
or metalloids.
And, in some instances,

00:07:30.830 --> 00:07:34.490
they can be made to behave more
nearly metallic.

00:07:34.490 --> 00:07:38.160
And in other cases,
they behave more nearly as

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:41.830
insulators. So,
now with this framework,

00:07:41.830 --> 00:07:45.490
I said that talking about these
valence electrons might give us some

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:49.160
insight into chemical reactivity.
What can we say about chemical

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:53.230
reactivity?
Well, what do we know about extremes

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:57.690
of chemical reactivity?
See if we can grab onto something.

00:07:57.690 --> 00:08:02.150
We know that at one extreme we have
no chemical reactivity.

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:06.610
We have elements that are totally
inert, and we have examples of this,

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:11.070
the noble gases, dominantly inert.
I know it's possible to induce

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:15.530
chemical reactions,
but these are exceptions.

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:34.126
This is not the norm. So,
we have an inertness.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:24.920
And at the other end we have
explosive reaction.

00:08:24.920 --> 00:08:29.840
OK, so do we know anything so far
that we can point to that would give

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:34.760
us a departure?
And the answer is yes,

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:39.690
we know something about the noble
gases. What do we know about the

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:44.610
noble gases? They are chemically
inert. They have the highest values.

00:08:44.610 --> 00:08:49.530
They have the highest average
valence electron energy

00:08:49.530 --> 00:09:07.193
in any shell.
And, the electron configuration is

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
always ns2p6. Whatever the n number
is, with the exception of helium,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:47.000
helium is the oddity because there's
only two elements in n equals one

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:53.000
shell. But, once you get beyond n
equals one, it's always 2s2,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:59.000
2p6, 3s2, 3s6. So, we have an octet
of the electrons that seems to be

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:05.000
associated with chemical inertness.
Octet stability is the term applied

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:11.000
to this feature.
So, all right, let's go with this.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Let's say, suppose we hypothesize
that an octet of the electrons is

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.000
going to lead to stability.
Is there some place we can go next

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:29.000
with this? And I say,
well, let's look at something like

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:35.000
sodium. Let's look at sodium.
Sodium has the electronic structure

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:40.000
1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s1.
Now, that's not an octet,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
but it's not far. This is the
electronic structure of neon.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
So it's really sodium you can think
of electronically as neon plus the

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
3s1 electron. It's so close.
And, I also know something else

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
about sodium. It's got a very low
average valence electron energy.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Its average valence electron energy
is 5.2 electron volts,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
which is a heck of a lot less than
11.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:28.140
So, this is a good metal.
It's a good electron donor.

00:10:28.140 --> 00:10:32.280
So, I've got something that's one
electron away from the electronic

00:10:32.280 --> 00:10:36.420
structure of neon.
It's a good electron donor.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:40.560
If it could only ditch this
electron, it could have the same

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:44.710
electronic structure as neon.
But you can't just ditch an

00:10:44.710 --> 00:10:48.850
electron. Charge neutrality won't
allow for it. If you want to lose

00:10:48.850 --> 00:11:08.700
electron, you have to find someplace
for that electron to go.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:57.700
In other words,
for an electron donor to give up its

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:02.410
electron, the electron donor needs
to have an electron acceptor.

00:11:02.410 --> 00:11:07.110
So, that's sort of half the story.
Now, let's go over to the other

00:11:07.110 --> 00:11:11.820
side. Let's look at chlorine.
Chlorine is 1s2, 2s2, 2p6, 3s2,

00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:16.520
3p5. The chlorine, it's not an
octet here. This is five plus two

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:21.230
is seven. But,
when I went to school,

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:25.940
seven was only one less than eight.
So, this needs only one more

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:30.640
electron. If it could gain one more
electron, then chlorine would be

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:35.850
iso-electronic with argon.
So, it would achieve octet stability.

00:11:35.850 --> 00:11:41.570
And we know that chlorine is very
aggressive when it comes to

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:47.280
electrons. It's got an average
valence electron energy of about 16

00:11:47.280 --> 00:12:04.426
eV, 16.5 eV, which is a
lot greater than 11.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:57.900
So, what if we were to put the two
of these in the same room?

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:02.810
You've got an electron donor with a
powerful urge to become neon-like.

00:12:02.810 --> 00:12:07.720
You've got an electron acceptor
with the powerful urge to become

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:12.630
argon like. What if we were to take
this electron and send it over to

00:12:12.630 --> 00:12:17.540
here, in other words,
engage in electron transfer.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:22.900
What will we achieve?
Sodium would become sodium plus.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:28.720
Chlorine would become chlorine
minus. So, I've got ion pair

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:34.540
formation, and I've got a huge
decrease in energy because a donor

00:12:34.540 --> 00:12:40.360
is able to express that urge,
an acceptor is able to express that

00:12:40.360 --> 00:12:46.180
urge. And, I've achieved octet
stability in a new way.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:13:04.093
But there's more because now I've
got pluses and minuses.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:57.090
This is all gas phase.
It's all gas phase. So,

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:02.180
what happens if I put pluses and
minuses in a gas phase?

