00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:11.630
When you get one over R, you get a
gradual fall. If you get one over R

00:20:11.630 --> 00:20:16.540
squared, it'll be a little steeper.
One over R to the sixth will come

00:20:16.540 --> 00:20:20.770
in, and then jump off precipitously.
And that's what you want because the

00:20:20.770 --> 00:20:24.330
electron repulsion is only felt when
you are in really,

00:20:24.330 --> 00:20:27.880
really close. And then,
it's, for all intents and purposes,

00:20:27.880 --> 00:20:31.440
falls to zero. So, the Born
exponent typically takes values of

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:34.990
between six and 12.
And, B is some constant that we

00:20:34.990 --> 00:20:38.550
have to determine.
So, what's one over R to the 8th

00:20:38.550 --> 00:20:42.100
going to look like on this scale?
It's going to look like this. It's

00:20:42.100 --> 00:20:45.660
going to hug the x axis until it
